description:
sak json subcommands read stdin automatically when no file arg is given, but passing the conventional "-" stdin sentinel is treated as a literal filename and fails:

  echo '{"a":1}' | sak json query ".a" -    # sak: error: cannot read: -: No such file or directory (os error 2)  (exit 2)
  echo '{"a":1}' | sak json query ".a"      # 1   (exit 0)

"-" meaning stdin is a near-universal Unix convention (cat, jq, grep, etc.), so users (and LLMs) reach for it reflexively when building pipelines like `sak k8s get ... | sak json query ... -`. Getting a "No such file" error instead is confusing and costs a retry.

Fix: treat a file argument of exactly "-" as stdin across all sak json subcommands (query, select, keys, flatten, paths, grep, schema, diff, validate). Likely a one-line change at the path-resolution chokepoint. Consider applying the same convention to other file-consuming domains (config, csv, cert) for consistency.

Found while diagnosing an OOMKill, alongside sak-llm-k8s-get-ndjson-items-path.
